  <scopecontent>
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>The Collection on Léon Seyffers is a post-custodial digital collection managed by the University of Pittsburgh, which brings together the resources of several archival institutions. Records include digital surrogates of family photographs, personal administrative records, deportation documents, postwar art restitution records, and photos of missing and restituted art.Contributors include the Kazerne Dossin Memorial, Museum and Documentation Center; De Vriidagavond; the Belgian Federal Public Service Economy; the Belgian State Archives; the U.S. National Archives Records Administration; Fold3 Historical Military Records; FamilySearch and Museum Leuven. The mission of this archival program is to illuminate the life and untimely death of art dealer and collector Léon Seyffers and his family during the final days of World War II as well as track the postwar journey of his extensive art collection.

This collection focuses on the life of Léon Seyffers (1885-1944), which includes references to the Jewish community in Brussels, Belgium, and the postwar art restitution of his art collection. While most records date from 1900-1950, early-life documents (1885) are included. The Collection on Léon Seyffers also includes records about his family: his wife Sarah Seyffers (née Krellstein, 1899-1944), son Maxime Seyffers (1929-1944), daughter Myriam Seyffers (1931-1944), niece Freddy Coster (1925-1933), sister Bertha Seyffers (1898-1988), nephew Maurice Coster (1928-2019), and sister-in-law Berthe Krellestein (dates unknown). Geographic areas mentioned in the collection are Brussels, Anderlecht, Leuven, and Mechelen, Belgium; Amsterdam, Netherlands; and Jüchen, Munich, and Düsseldorf, Germany; and Oświęcim (Auschwitz), Poland.</p>  
</scopecontent>
  <bioghist>
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Collection materials relate to the life and work of Léon Seyffers (1885-1994), a Belgian art collector and dealer who lived in Brussels until 1944 when he and his family (wife Sarah along with children Maxime and Myriam) were transported to the Mechelen documentation center and then onto Auschwitz where they are presumed to have died..</p>  
</bioghist>
